# Math Point Type Rule

- When editing math-related code, include `packages/math/src/types.ts` in context.
- Use canonical tuple point types `GlobalPoint | LocalPoint` instead of ad-hoc `{ x, y }` object types or non-existent `Point`.
- If a local alias is introduced, it must alias `GlobalPoint | LocalPoint`.
- Keep math utility signatures and generics consistent with existing exports, for example `P extends GlobalPoint | LocalPoint`.
- Keep container types aligned with `types.ts` patterns (for example `Line<P>`, `LineSegment<P>`, `Triangle<P>`, `Polygon<P>` where `P extends GlobalPoint | LocalPoint`).

## How to verify

- Confirm math changes reference existing types from `packages/math/src/types.ts`.
- Confirm coordinate signatures use `GlobalPoint | LocalPoint` (or a documented alias to that union), not `Point`.
- Confirm generic constraints follow exported patterns (for example `P extends GlobalPoint | LocalPoint`).
- Confirm no new inline `{ x, y }` point type literals are introduced in math APIs.
- Confirm exports remain type-compatible with package consumers.
